In the meantime, take care of your autumn leaves. There are various methods for drying and preserving autumn leaves, and they don’t take the same amount of time as flowers, so get to work. You can choose to:

Microwave them. Try microwaving your leaves until they’re completely dry, between double layers of paper towels. Be careful, though, as they could catch on fire. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/5\/50\/Make-an-Autumn-Bunch-Step-4Bullet1.jpg\/v4-460px-Make-an-Autumn-Bunch-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/5\/50\/Make-an-Autumn-Bunch-Step-4Bullet1.jpg\/v4-760px-Make-an-Autumn-Bunch-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}


Use wax paper. Place a leaf between two pieces of wax paper, place a towel on top and press it with an iron to seal the wax paper. Do both sides and then cut around the leaf. Carefully peel the wax paper off. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/a\/ab\/Make-an-Autumn-Bunch-Step-4Bullet2.jpg\/v4-460px-Make-an-Autumn-Bunch-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/a\/ab\/Make-an-Autumn-Bunch-Step-4Bullet2.jpg\/v4-760px-Make-an-Autumn-Bunch-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}


Soak them in glycerine solution. Mix glycerine and water so that it’s one part glycerine and two parts water - you'll need about one cup of solution. Pour the solution into a flat pan, place the leaves in and put some kind of weight (such as a plate) on the leaves to keep them submerged. Soak them for 2-6 days and then dry them gently with a paper towel. This method helps keep the leaves more flexible. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/6\/61\/Make-an-Autumn-Bunch-Step-4Bullet3.jpg\/v4-460px-Make-an-Autumn-Bunch-Step-4Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/6\/61\/Make-an-Autumn-Bunch-Step-4Bullet3.jpg\/v4-760px-Make-an-Autumn-Bunch-Step-4Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

It also helps to spray the leaves with hairspray once you’re done with drying them, to keep them preserved. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/7\/73\/Make-an-Autumn-Bunch-Step-4Bullet4.jpg\/v4-460px-Make-an-Autumn-Bunch-Step-4Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/7\/73\/Make-an-Autumn-Bunch-Step-4Bullet4.jpg\/v4-760px-Make-an-Autumn-Bunch-Step-4Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

text:
 Gather the things you’ll need. Remember that there’s no strict list; you can mix and match what you like. You can gather a variety of differently sized and coloured autumn leaves, or make them all identical. It’s generally best to stick with medium sized to small leaves though, as you want the bunches to be graceful, not oversized and untidy. As for autumn plants, you can take your pick depending on where you live; pine cones, berries or flowers. Make sure all of your items stick to a colour palette; typically, you’ll be looking for a range of auburn, browns, gold and reds. Make sure that the ribbon you select adds the ultimate touch – a deep red or gold ribbon, or perhaps a striped or checked one, will be perfect. When gathering your items, remember the following:
Your flowers should be removed from sunlight as soon as they are cut so that they will dry with their colours preserved. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/0\/07\/Make-an-Autumn-Bunch-Step-2Bullet1.jpg\/v4-460px-Make-an-Autumn-Bunch-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/0\/07\/Make-an-Autumn-Bunch-Step-2Bullet1.jpg\/v4-760px-Make-an-Autumn-Bunch-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Your flowers should also not be fully mature; else they will lose their petals quickly. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/8\/8e\/Make-an-Autumn-Bunch-Step-2Bullet2.jpg\/v4-460px-Make-an-Autumn-Bunch-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/8\/8e\/Make-an-Autumn-Bunch-Step-2Bullet2.jpg\/v4-760px-Make-an-Autumn-Bunch-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"} Dry your flowers. You can use the microwave technique for drying daises or roses, or tie your flowers in small bunches and hang them upside down in a dark, dry area such as an unused closet. Allow your flowers to dry for two to three weeks. Yes, this takes time and patience, but it ensures that your bunch lasts longer and makes it look all the more attractive. Dry your autumn leaves. In the meantime, take care of your autumn leaves. There are various methods for drying and preserving autumn leaves, and they don’t take the same amount of time as flowers, so get to work. You can choose to:

